FRESH FACTS ABOUT FIELDING

THE general reader, as a rule, is but moderately interested in minor rectifications. Secure in a conven- tional preference of the spirit to the letter, he pro- fesses to be indifferent whether the grandmother of an exalted personage was a “ Hugginson'’ or a “ Blenkinsop'' ; and he is equally careless as to the correct Christian names of his cousins and his aunts. In the main, the general reader is wise in his genera- tion. But with the painful biographer, toiling in the immeasurable sand of thankless research, often foot-sore and dry of throat, these trivialities assume exaggerated proportions; and to those who remind him-—as in a cynical age he is sure to be reminded— of the infinitesimal value of his hard-gotten grains of information‚ he can only reply mournfussy, if uncon- vincingly, that fact is fact—even in matters of mustard-seed. With this prelude, I propose to set down one or two minute points concerning Henry Fielding, not yet comprised in any existing records of

his career.¹·
